air Wallach walked the streets of Jerusalem to consider the graffiti, logos, inscriptions, official signs, and ephemera that transformed the city over the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. As these urban texts became a tool in the service of capitalism, nationalism, and colonialism, the affinities of Arabic and Hebrew were forgotten and these sister-languages found themselves locked in a bitter war. Looking at the writing of—and literally on—Jerusalem, Wallach offers a creative and expansive history of the city, a fresh take on modern urban texts, and a new reading of the Israel/Palestine conflict through its material culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and historyzJerusalem. 0aWritten communicationzJerusalem. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh  aIsrael studies.  aJerusalem.  aJewish studies.  aOttoman Empire.  aPalestine studies.  acolonialism.  ainscriptions.  amaterial culture.  atextuality.  aurban studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361114640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503611146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503611146/original  a978-3-11-069218-1  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles